In the end, the generational upheaval ripping through the
Democratic caucus stopped short of ushering Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez into l=
eadership. For the past several weeks, House minority leader Hakeem Jeffrie=
s stood back and allowed junior members to challenge the old guard for seni=
or committee assignments. Alas, A.O.C., who squared off against 74-year-old=
 Gerry Connolly for the ranking member post at Oversight, didn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve an ally in Nancy Pelosi, who spent the weekend rolling
calls=E2=80=94still operating behind the scenes even as she recovered from =
emergency hip replacement surgery in Germany=E2=80=94to ensure that Ocasio-=
Cortez lost.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, Pelosi wasn=E2=80=99t the only Democrat invested in preventing t=
he media-savvy, 35-year-old Squad member from gaining an even bigger platfo=
rm. As it turns out, there are many caucus members who still resent Ocasio-=
Cortez for her history of clashing with popular
colleagues. Add to that the free-floating, post-election anxiety about the =
viability of A.O.C.=E2=80=99s progressive style of politics. Indeed, the mo=
re moderate members of the party I spoke to expressed concern that elevatin=
g A.O.C. to Oversight=E2=80=94a role that would put her front and center on=
 C-SPAN and the nightly news=E2=80=94would not help Dems with their much-ne=
eded brand rebuild. On Monday, she lost a vote of the party steering commit=
tee. On Tuesday, she lost the vote among the full Democratic
caucus, 131 to 84.

