argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Down in D.C., <em>The</em> <em>Washington Post =
</em>spent Tuesday
evening doling out awards to its journalists=E2=80=94a historically joyous,=
 navel-gazing holiday tradition, albeit one that was considerably less enjo=
yable this year. The annual ceremony, awarding both the Ben Bradlee Award f=
or Courage in Journalism and the Eugene Meyer Awards, was subsumed by the g=
rowing miasma of incompetence and bickering. To wit: There was the departur=
e of <strong>Matea Gold</strong>, the veteran managing editor who is decamp=
ing to <em>The New York Times </em>after being passed over
during C.E.O. <strong>Will Lewis</strong>=E2=80=99s grand search for a new =
executive editor. And then there=E2=80=99s the general malaise brought on b=
y years of declining readership, revenue losses, and managerial controversy=
=2E Somewhere, <strong>Fred Ryan </stro=
ng>is pouring himself a stiff drink in=
 a tartan jacket and expressing gratitude that he isn=E2=80=99t cleaning up=
 the mess.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">By the time Posties had gathered on Tuesda=
y
afternoon, <em>sans</em> Lewis, their discontent had been exacerbated by an=
 item in Axios alleging that several of Lewis=E2=80=99s top candidates to r=
un the paper, including the <em>Times</em>=E2=80=99s <strong>Cliff Levy </s=
trong>and former <em>Post </em>editor <strong>Anne Kornblut</strong>, had w=
ithdrawn from consideration due to reservations about Lewis=E2=80=99s =E2=
=80=9Cfoggy and uninspiring=E2=80=9D vision. It=E2=80=99s still not entirel=
y clear whether <em>Levy</em> privately expressed his reservations before W=
ill might have conveyed
his own, but a bad situation had once again gotten worse. As I understand i=
t, many of the folks Will might have been able to recruit for the position =
(Cliff, Matea, etcetera) weren=E2=80=99t the ones he <em>really </em>wanted=
, and the ones he wanted weren=E2=80=99t<em> really </em>interested.</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">In any event, this all made for a particularly depressing sta=
te of affairs amidst the mistletoe and holly. And the evening=E2=80=99s
festivities truly hit rock bottom, as my buddy <strong>Oliver Darcy </stron=
g>has reported, when veteran sports columnist <strong>Sally Jenkins </stron=
g>said in prepared remarks, =E2=80=9CThis newsroom has been fractured. What=
 I want for Christmas is, I want this place whole again,=E2=80=9D then proc=
eeded to tear up along with other colleagues.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Inc=
reasingly, Lewis=E2=80=99s critics fear that he doesn=E2=80=99t actually <e=
m>have</em>
a vision for the paper. In private conversations, however, he has described=
 a plan that sounds like a more refined version of the one he laid out shor=
tly after his arrival more than a year ago. His strategy, as articulated in=
 these conversations, is to make the <em>Post</em> the news source for =E2=
=80=9Call of America,=E2=80=9D with a high-low approach that simultaneously=
 draws elite readers while making derivative content more interesting and l=
ess partisan. According to this vision, the <em>Post</em> will have
three legs: a main newsroom, led by the yet-to-be-determined executive edit=
or; the high-end, Politico Pro-style, <strong>Marty Kady</strong>-led subsc=
ription project called =E2=80=9CPost Intelligence=E2=80=9D; and that infamo=
us =E2=80=9Cthird newsroom,=E2=80=9D dubbed =E2=80=9CPost Ventures,=E2=80=
=9D which will oversee new initiatives and acquisitions.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><a href=3D"https=
