=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhile, House Democrats voted 121 to 91=
 to <em>approve</em> a
bid by A.O.C.=E2=80=99s largely anonymous 2018 classmate, Minnesota=E2=80=
=99s <strong>Angie Craig</strong>, to depose 79-year-old <strong>David Scot=
t</strong> as ranking member of Agriculture. Craig=E2=80=99s ascension repr=
esents a win for a younger generation in Congress, especially as the party =
seeks to elevate scrappier, more aggressive talent=E2=80=94like <strong>Jam=
ie Raskin</strong>, who is taking over as ranking on Judiciary=E2=80=94over=
 the old guard. But it also reflects a debate among Democrats over which <e=
m>type</em> of
talent is best positioned to lead the resistance from the minority. Craig, =
a moderate who has been ranked among the most bipartisan members of Congres=
s, won her swing district in a landslide. In short, she=E2=80=99s precisely=
 the kind of Democrat that some in the party want to represent them in the =
<strong>Trump</strong> era.<br/><br/>The divergent fates of Ocasio-Cortez a=
nd Craig also illustrate the enduring truism that it takes more than intern=
et clout, or movement support, to take power on the Hill.
(This is a bicameral and bipartisan principle, as the MAGA wing learned whe=
n <strong>John Thune</strong> bested their preferred candidate, <strong>Ric=
k Scott</strong>, for Senate majority leader.) And unlike A.O.C., Craig is =
widely popular in the caucus and is strategic in picking fights. =E2=80=9CP=
art of it is getting your relationships right,=E2=80=9D a former member inv=
olved in the races told me. The endless first-term fighting between A.O.C. =
and Pelosi also alienated the many, <em>many</em> members who=E2=80=99ve
supported Pelosi for years. A.O.C.=E2=80=99s sparring with Jeffries in that=
 same era also stirred fears among rank-and-file colleagues that she would =
support primary challengers against them.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">That=E2=80=99s not to say=
 Craig lacks boldness: She was a key figure in the Capitol Hill effort to g=
et <strong>Joe Biden</strong> to withdraw from the presidential election la=
st summer, when many of her colleagues (A.O.C. included) were either
backing him or lying low. And in challenging Scott, she was once again sayi=
ng the quiet part out loud, voicing her concerns about the septuagenarian=
=E2=80=99s health at a time when most of her colleagues were only doing so =
privately. Craig has thus limited her battles to the ones where the caucus =
was essentially behind her=E2=80=94even if other members lacked the will to=
 follow through themselves.=C2=A0</p></div>
